## **Application Questions**

**Why do you want to participate in our Break Through Tech AI program? What are your personal, academic, or professional goals for participating in this program? \* (required,250 word limit)**  
This program is a unique opportunity involving faculty I admire, Professor Reinman, collaboration over real datasets from partnering companies, and guidance from mentors and company challenge advisors. I aim to expand my exploration of AI's tremendous potential both academically and professionally, and this comprehensive program offers both within a like-minded community dedicated to empowering women.  
	I'm eager to participate as this program perfectly aligns with my passion for leveraging technology to address real-world challenges. As a piano and computer science double major, I hope to use what I'll learn in this program to achieve my personal goal, my sole proprietorship's first product aimed at fellow musicians and bridging the disconnect between listening to the music we play and practicing it. This aspect of practicing is often understressed but crucial, as it trains our ears to make interpretive decisions that set one musician apart from another. Thus, I've always dreamed of an application that uses audio recognition machine learning like Shazam and Siri, but to make accessible digital sheet music with automated score following. This can not only bridge the disconnect in ear practicing, but also help the visually impaired learn by ear and raise disability awareness.  
I aim to unite my extensive musical and artistic backgrounds with my computer science major and passion for AI into innovative solutions that broaden the scope in which AI is deployed. I've taken UCLA's ML and NLP electives, but Break Through Tech AI offers invaluable mentorship, connections, and industry experience that my curriculum lacks.

**What interests or excites you about a possible career in AI, machine learning, data science or related fields? \* (required,250 word limit)**  
	Technology is now one of the most ubiquitous and diverse fields today. I want to make an impact on the public, and using technology as a tool can reach the farthest and widest of audiences. Whether it be arts, writing, sciences, law, etc. technology is transforming how all these disciplines are materialized and put into action to define the future of civilization. Sure, I can be a professional pianist and strive to follow the footsteps of the legendary pianists before me, but I want to explore the uncharted waters of weaponizing technology's interdisciplinary potential.  
Just like the broader "technology", AI has endless potential in all fields and has lately been especially rapid in proving its many uses. My experience in Stanford OHS's competitive FIRST robotics club first kindled my passion for AI with live computer vision decision-making. As ChatGPT took the world by storm my sophomore year and I studied the surprisingly intuitive conception of remarkable machine learning designs in my UCLA electives, I became more enamored.   
I'm fascinated with the prospect of turning ideas targeting current problems into accessible and well-designed solutions. Every day, I notice how AI can enrich our lives with both breakthroughs in possibility and relief from tediousness; I'm contributing to an open-source sign language recognition project that resembles 18-year-old Google Translate in its infancy. I'm also currently training an algorithm to match audio inputs of a piece's performance to sheet music to facilitate more efficient learning from the tediousness of today's seemingly archaic ear training.

**Tell us about your experience with relevant extracurricular activities (clubs, hackathons, volunteer work, etc.) and any leadership roles that you have played. \* (required,250 word limit)**  
In UCLA's Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) AI branch and Society of Women Engineers (SWE) clubs, I organized hackathons and connected with industry panelists, interns, and my now invaluable mentor, a fellow female currently working in tech. Both participating and helping guide these inclusive communities have been immensely enriching in sparking my passion for AI and expanding my collaborating and developing skills. I'm also proud to have been selected by the T. Howard Diversity-TECH program for my qualities.   
In my 14 years training formally as a classical pianist and winning first place at the 2023 UCLA Benno Rubinyi competition, I've also realized how equally rewarding it is to share my music extracurricularly. In high school, I collaborated with a classmate violinist to perform concerts for Aegis Living senior home residents. Their warm embrace of our music inspires me to this day, where I volunteer every quarter to give a half-hour recital to retired UCLA faculty at the Chancellor's home. I'm also a self-taught artist all my life ([deviantart.com/gracethelittleartist](https://www.deviantart.com/gracethelittleartist/gallery)) with customers and art continues to bring inspiration and creativity into my life.   
	While juggling my double major in music and compsci, I also have a full-stack apprenticeship with Applied Coding. I receive mentorship and collaborate in a scrum team to develop the startup's website UI components, backend authentication API, and resume ATS ML algorithm. I learn to adapt fast to current industry tools like Typescript, Node.js, MongoDB, and Flask Python on an existing repo. 

**Please describe a tech-related project completed or achievement that you have received and why you are proud of this accomplishment. \* (required,250 word limit)**  
	My time management app, DreamTeam ([https://github.com/gracchen/DreamTeam](https://github.com/gracchen/DreamTeam)), is a full-stack application to increase my own academic productivity. Since this passion project emerged from personal necessity \- challenges of navigating a double major, apprenticeship, and lifelong dedication to fine arts \- I developed my own calendar scheduling app. After daily use, I added more user-friendly features like customizable presets of repeating tasks by days of the week for auto-scheduling. My streamlined scheduling app with intuitive features like drag-n-drop functionality empowered me to efficiently juggle exams, project deadlines, and daily routines, all while ensuring I allocated enough time for piano practice.  
I'm idea-driven and conceived this idea long before knowing the best tools and languages to use. When other scheduling apps I tried didn't fit my needs, I prototyped a desktop app in Java Swing, but it quickly outgrew Swing's deprecated API when I needed mobile porting to move it to mobile. Due to the speedier pacing of mobile advancement rendering Swing outdated, I realized my best option was to restart with better chosen tools that provide and anticipate widespread support while complimenting a thorough roadmap of my app's future. That's when I tried Gluon Scenebuilder, a plugin worth a steep learning curve by offering far more efficient workflows for arranging UI components. Combined with the new, ubiquitous JavaFX, my app was reborn\! This project opened my eyes to how to choose the optimal combination of tools for the job, something already taken care of within the bubble of school projects. 

**Describe a time when you worked on a team to accomplish a shared goal. What was the goal of your team? What role did you play? What did your team accomplish? \* (required,250 word limit)**  
	I chose to be the front-end development lead for FloraFauna ([http://jzhi.bol.ucla.edu](http://jzhi.bol.ucla.edu)), an open-ended group project where we made a crowdsourcing geographical app for wildlife enthusiasts in the latest React and Node.js frameworks. This social media forum unites animal watching hobbyists, experts polling population data, and casual nature enthusiasts around the world to share local wildlife spottings through photos, geographic data and community votes on species identification.  
Through our frequent meetings, I proposed, designed, and prototyped the placement of all the features we ended up implementing. I drew a mockup on paper and then in Figma for a well thought out, interactive model that the final website recreates faithfully, and also proposed more user-friendly features like a "get current location" button and more concise search navigation headers. I also coded two of the webpages with coordinated Git version control, and helped backend teammates better design their APIs to our frontend needs.  
It was also my first glimpse into collaborative software development that resembles real industry practices. Our team expertly planned all the tasks, assigned roles that capitalize on each teammate's strengths, and carefully coordinated simultaneously developing features to address any dependencies between sub-teams. Combined with the eagerness to uphold our responsibilities and to help each other, our team easily finished everything in our concretely defined specifications with plenty of time to spare. This experience taught me the numerous essential ingredients that compose this experience in bringing about a smooth, peaceful, and efficient outcome. 

**Break Through Tech AI aims to create a pathway for underrepresented women into the fields of AI, machine learning, and data science. Our program intentionally fosters a safe and inclusive community that welcomes female-identifying students as well as members of other underrepresented groups in these fields. Why do you want to learn in this environment and our community? \* (required,250 word limit)**  
	Growing up into fine arts and classical music, I'd always seen my future in arts. However, my passion for gaming, 3D modelling, and tinkering with phones and desktops led me to explore the field of computer science. I formally double majored in piano performance and computer science at the end of freshman year at UCLA. This unconventional background gives me a unique perspective on the potential in intersecting arts and technology, inspiring me to train an ML algorithm with midi spectrograms for my dream application.   
As a female student embarking on an untraditional journey into AI, my background makes it easy for peers and professors to doubt my ability as an engineer and I used to struggle with impostor syndrome my first few quarters. However, I know my own abilities now and so joining Break Through Tech AI is my dream opportunity to continue building my confidence, skills, and commitment to breaking gender and diversity barriers in AI. I believe a diverse community brings well-rounded, innovative solutions, provides a first-line defense against AI models trained on marginalized, inaccurate data/assumptions, and enriches this program's learning experience for everyone involved.   
Being part of this program also brings the chance to connect with like-minded individuals on similar paths to finding their place in AI and sharing my passion for using AI to address real-world challenges. I look forward to both learning from and bringing unique experiences to the community to collectively shape a more inclusive future for AI, machine learning, and data science.

**50-300 words:**  
**Tell us about a time when you performed a task without all the information you may have needed. How did you approach and address the situation? \***

I aimed to design and develop a time scheduling app when I noticed my preferences for a week based to do list with customizable presets were not compatible with other apps on the market. I was familiar with desktop frameworks but not Java specifically, so I didn't know what to use at first. I opted for Java Swing first before realizing it was too outdated because a lot of libraries were deprecated and tutorials and community support regarding Swing were very few and outdated.  

It was a hard but essential lesson for me to learn. I started more carefully choosing the tools that would speed up my process, finding the active Javafx toolkit and it's companion addon, Gluon Scenebuilder which vastly streamlined the front-end design process compared to my struggle with Swing. This was because it turned the coding of UI design from typing to drag and drop and property tweaking along a preview, which saved countless hours of tweaking and testing code manually. I also chose JDBC and clever cloud in my search for mysql cloud APIs compatible with Java which allowed for a free cloud hosted database that my app could connect to, retrieve from and push changes to, and remember its states remotely. By not knowing everything about how to make this app, I trained myself to tailor my tools and languages to what I needed, not the other way around.

**It seems like there is a mobile app, website or device for just about everything these days. If you could design a new product that would make an immediate impact for consumers, what would that be? You can describe a new app, a new website, a new device or a new process or system. Be sure to focus on why this new product is needed, and what would make it successful. (250 word limit)**

As a musician, we all experience a certain disconnect between listening to the music we play and practicing their written notes. It's crucial for us to study audio recordings while we learn to transform our own subconscious artistic inclinations to educated, purposeful decisions. These conscious decisions are what set one musician apart from another. 

This is why I've always dreamed of an application that, given any music recording, use machine learning to match each unit (measure) of the written piece (score) to a timestamp of the recording. Practicing with the ear would be far more convenient and precise, as the app allows students to easily summon the timestamp of a diffcult passage with one tap on that passage on a digitalized score. They can train their ears to the effect of different interpretations by using this app for both their own playing and that of various masters, and easily switch between them. 

I notice my piano classmates are prefering tablets over hard copies of music, and cannot believe such a tool doesn't exist yet. Instead, we are still stumbling over recordings sometimes an hour long, trying to navigate to the place we are looking for, like we were 100 years ago. This makes such a crucial part of our development a chore. With the arrival of voice recognition and Shazam, an app that takes an audio snippet of music and identifies it's name, an app to match recordings to scores isn't far fetched and has equal potential.

**Describe a time when you had to explain a complex technical topic to someone with little to no technical know-how. How did you approach it? (150 words) \***  
I was explaining to my mom why my issues with porting my JavaFX desktop application to android could not be solved with buying an Android phone. She thought I was being a cheapskate.  
I explained that the issue isn't about having a phone to test, because when I am coding on my computer, my computer can open up a new window, like FireFox, but instead of FireFox, it can run pretty much identically to how a physical android phone can.   
I then explained the compiling issues. The architecture of the android phone is very different from that of my computer, which is why in order for my code to also work on a phone, it needs lots of converting. However, android architecture changes faster than a computer's and there is no official, up-to-date tool for porting, so the issue lies in that.
